%I A396915 #12 Jun 14 2026 23:18:49
%S A396915 130,145,305,689,1745,1870,1970,2353,2930,3205,3538,3845,4069,5105,
%T A396915 5122,5905,7093,7397,7445,7570,9074,9077,9701,11345,12130,12270,13445,
%U A396915 15602,16642,17873,18545,19253,21205,21922,22181,22805,23330,25909,27505,31057,31429,31697
%N A396915 Composite squarefree numbers k such that k' + 2*k is a perfect square, where k' is the arithmetic derivative of k (A003415).
%C A396915 Motivated by Erdős Problem 307, which asks for finite sets of primes P and Q with (Sum_{p in P} 1/p)*(Sum_{q in Q} 1/q) = 1. If A' = B and B' = A is a 2-cycle of the arithmetic derivative (with A, B squarefree, this gives such a solution), then N = A*B satisfies N' + 2*N = (A+B)^2 and N' - 2*N = (A-B)^2, so both N' - 2*N and N' + 2*N are perfect squares. This sequence imposes only the plus condition. The minus condition N' - 2*N = square requires N' >= 2*N, i.e., Sum_{p|N} 1/p >= 2 for squarefree N, which forces N >= 2*3*5*...*277 > 10^112; so no term of the intersection can be found by direct search.
%C A396915 Theorem: for every odd prime l dividing a term k, the cofactor k/l is a nonzero quadratic residue mod l. Proof: for squarefree k = l*m, k' = m + l*m' == m (mod l), so s^2 = k' + 2*k == m (mod l), and m !== 0 (mod l) since k is squarefree.
%C A396915 Semiprime terms k = p*q satisfy (2*p+1)*(2*q+1) = 2*s^2 + 1 where s^2 = k' + 2*k, and necessarily p == q == 1 (mod 4). Proof: (2*s)^2 == -2 (mod r) for every prime r dividing 2*p+1, so r == 1 or 3 (mod 8), hence 2*p+1 == 1 or 3 (mod 8) and p == 0 or 1 (mod 4); p = 2 is impossible since s^2 = 5*q + 2 == 2 (mod 5) has no solution (and q = 5 fails directly).
%C A396915 Conjecturally infinite: for terms of the form 5*q one needs 11*q + 5 = s^2, i.e., q = (s^2 - 5)/11 with s == +-4 (mod 11); s even is equivalent to q == 1 (mod 4). Bunyakovsky's conjecture applied to this quadratic gives infinitely many prime values q, hence infinitely many terms 5*q.
%C A396915 The counting function appears to be ~ 0.25*sqrt(X) (square-density heuristic; the observed ratio is 0.2549 at X = 2*10^5 and 0.2510 at X = 10^6), suggesting a(n) ~ 16*n^2.
%H A396915 Thomas F. Bloom, <a href="https://www.erdosproblems.com/307">Problem 307</a>, Erdős Problems.
%F A396915 For semiprime terms k = p*q with s^2 = k' + 2*k: (2*p+1)*(2*q+1) = 2*s^2 + 1.
%e A396915 130 = 2*5*13 is a term: 130' = 101 and 101 + 2*130 = 361 = 19^2.
%e A396915 145 = 5*29 is a term: 145' = 34 and 34 + 2*145 = 324 = 18^2.
%p A396915 with(numtheory): readlib(issqr): P:=proc(k); if issqrfree(k) and not isprime(k)
%p A396915 then if issqr(k*add(op(2,p)/op(1,p),p=ifactors(k)[2])+2*k) then k; fi; fi; end:
%p A396915 seq(P(i),i=2..10^5); # _Paolo P. Lava_, Jun 10 2026
%o A396915 (Python)
%o A396915 from math import isqrt
%o A396915 from sympy import factorint
%o A396915 def ok(n):
%o A396915     f = factorint(n)
%o A396915     if len(f) < 2 or max(f.values()) > 1: return False
%o A396915     d = sum(n//p for p in f)
%o A396915     return isqrt(d + 2*n)**2 == d + 2*n
%o A396915 print([n for n in range(2, 18000) if ok(n)])
%o A396915 (PARI)
%o A396915 ad(n) = my(f=factor(n)); n*sum(i=1, #f~, f[i, 2]/f[i, 1]);
%o A396915 isok(k) = issquarefree(k) && omega(k) > 1 && issquare(ad(k) + 2*k);
%Y A396915 Cf. A003415 (arithmetic derivative), A005117 (squarefree numbers), A120944 (composite squarefree numbers).
%Y A396915 Subsequence of A120944.
%K A396915 nonn,new
%O A396915 1,1
%A A396915 _Vico Bonfioli_, Jun 09 2026
